<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by RenewableUK to the Energy and Climate Change’s inquiry on Low carbon innovation</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by RenewableUK (LCI14)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">RenewableUK is the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">leading </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">renewable energy trade body, representing more than 600 members in the wind, wave and tidal sectors. These </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">industries will provide the majority of the renewable electricity required to meet the UK’s legally binding energy and emissions targets, create thousands of jobs across the supply chain, revitalise the economy and stabilise consumer energy bills</span><span style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Key issues:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.74pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Low Carbon Innovation Coordination Group</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> could provide better communication of its outputs as a group</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> to relevant stakeholders and those active in their technology focus areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.74pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Government has recognised the cont</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">ribution of wind and marine re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">newables</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> (and the role of innovation) towards its legally binding targets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">, however, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">low carbon innovation and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">the impact on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">lowering the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">Levelised Cost of E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">nergy could be improved.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.74pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">The innovation landscape, as a whole, is perceived as being</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> fragmented and needing a coordinated approach to communications</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.74pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">A long term commitment to low carbon innovation funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> and clarity on the policy frameworks for technology to be deployed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt"> is required to allow for innovative technologies to develop from con</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">cept to commercial reality.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11.5pt; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.74pt; padding-left:7.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">A key success factor in successful low carbon innovation will be Government, industry and academia working together to bring innovation to the market. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:12.45pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Government is committed to a contribution of 15% renewable energy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by 2020 as part of the EU Renewable Energy Directive.  Given the drive by both government and industry to lower the Levelised Cost of Energy and the role of renewables in reaching legally binding targets, it is important that innovation in the wind, wave a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd tidal renewable sectors is supported in order to provide a cost effective approach to achieving the UK’s legally binding emissions and energy targets for 2020 and beyond.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Low Carbon Innovation Coordination Group’s (LCICG) Technology Focus </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">areas at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> present include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> two of the technologies represented by Renewa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bleUK; offshore wind and marine (defined as wave and tidal) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">renewables.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although the UK has deployed more o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffshore wind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> than the rest of the world combined, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> technology is at a relatively im</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mature stage of development compared to more established technologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">potential for innovation has been recognised through a number of initiatives focussed on increasing efficiencies of the technologies with a view to cost reduction. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Innovation is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recognised contributing factor in the cost reduction agenda currently being faced by the renewables industry, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> particular </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relevance to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">offshore wind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as referenced in The Crown Estates Offshore Wind Cost Reduction Pathways Study</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cost Reduction </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Taskforce</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and subsequent workstream of the Offshore Wind </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Board dedicated to Technology and Innovation with a view to reducing costs in the industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Cost Reduction </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Pathways report has identified the potential for technology innovation and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mprovements in the supply chain to cut the cost of generating electricity by over 30% by 2020.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As highlighted in the National Audit Office’s review </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of Public</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> funding for innovation in low carbon </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technologies in the UK</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (figure 9), offshore wind could prove </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to provide the largest potential saving to the UK through innovation by 2050, as well as significant contributions to the UK economy (figure 10).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Offshore Renewable Energy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (ORE)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Catapult</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, recently established by the Technology Strategy Board,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is takin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g some of these issues forward, for example standardisation in offshore operations to contribute cost and risk reduction.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It is hoped the ORE Cata</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pult will act as a point to link industry, academia and the public sector in the technology areas of offshor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e wind, wave and tidal renewables.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a technology covered by the LCICG, offshore wind is set to play a key part in the UK meeting 2020 renewable energy targets.  Wave and Tidal renewables are currently in the array development stage, and hence should prove to be a contributing technology t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o the energy needs of the United Kingdom alongside a path of cost reduction as the technology develops to commercialisation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As such, marine energy has benefited from the Marine Energy Array Demonstration (MEAD).  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As key contributors to the UK’s energy mi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">x in years to come, efficiencies bought to renewables via innovation across the supply chain will play a vital role in the success of lowering the cost of energy, and therefore, Government support for innovation in wind, wave and ti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dal renewables will be w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elcomed at all stages of the technology development lifecycle.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At present, the Government’s support of innovation for offshore wind, wave and tidal renewables has been</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> widespread, with a number of support schemes.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he general approach to low carbon </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">innovation via the LCICG has been perceived as somewhat fragmented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">although </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the renewables industry has benefited from government support in the advancement and development of technology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The LCICG is aiming to maximise the impact of UK public sector fun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ding for low carbon technology</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> via coordination of the public sector support, improving communication, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">building a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> shared evidence base within low carbon innovation.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> membership consists of a number of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> public</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> funding and research bodies, who in thei</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r individual rights have contributed to supporting innovation in low carbon technologies.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a perceived lack of coordination between the various actors active in the low carbon innovation space, and their activities are not necessarily communicated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> effectively to those needing to access their services. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RenewableUK recommends the LCICG should aim to improve its outcomes in terms of communications with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> industry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> stakeholders and those wishing to take advantage knowledge and funding for innovation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> various innovation funding schemes would benefit from a more coordinated approach to identifying the programmes available for companies to apply for. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a group with access to an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">extensive knowledge base via the core and associate membership, the LCICG c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ould bring to the fore meaningful information and knowledge sharing is invaluable to those active in low carbon technology. This has been demonstrated through t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he LCICG’s Technology Innovation Needs Assessment (TINA) provid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a useful reference point for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the potential areas where innovation could impact on the cost reduction for offshore wind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(produced February 2012) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and marine technologies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(produced August 2012)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  With its forthcoming strategy for low carbon innovation, we would hope the LCICG will be ab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">le to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> clarify </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> aims and actions to provide coordination, communication and a shared evidence base for the various technology focus areas.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In turn, it would then be hoped, investment could be driven into low carbon technology by working closely with ind</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustry and identifying key areas contributing to the advancement of wind, wave and tidal renewable technologies.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The LCICG are currently in the process of implementing a pilot metric system to measure successes of investment into low carbon innovation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> top</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ics of capacity building, energy and economics.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  RenewableUK would welcome further information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and detail </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of this metric system in order to assess whether it would be applicable to onshore, offshore an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d marine renewable technologies, as well as whether </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the metric will be introduced as a standard measurement of progress and success in relation to strategy objectives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> across the LCICG membership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Inherently, innovation is difficult to measure, as there will always be a level of risk involved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ment of a particular technology.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The core members of the LCICG each focus on different levels of the Technology Readiness </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Scale and level in the supply chain in their approach to supporting low carbon innovation.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As such, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the LCICG supports innovation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in technologies across their development </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lifecycle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  For example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Energy Technologies Institute has examples of demonstrator projects</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for concepts at the applied research and development level.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Carbon Trust has projects in place where technology i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s being demonstrated at scale on projects in the water for offshore wind, wave and tidal. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> These projects have not been constrained to demonstrating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technology in British water, and have indeed seen their demonstration taking place on Continental European </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">offshore wind farms.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Schemes such as the Offshore Wind Component Technology Development and Demonstrator coordinated by DECC is an example of a scheme which could lead to investments for innovating companies based on their ability to demonstrate devices a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd component technologies for the larger  5+ MW plus turbines. These turbines are expected to be utilised on future offshore wind farms and will play a further role in the cost reduction of offshore wind.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The impact of short term funding timelines on pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ivate sector investment will vary according to the scale of the project.  Coupled with policy changes surrounding the support mechanism for renewable technology, there is a level of uncertainty surrounding the financing of projects and deployment of techno</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">logy. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Low carbon innovation is key to the development of low carbon technologies.  A combination of private and public sector investment will enable this to happen.  The renewables industry has faced and is facing a number of uncertainties for example, l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ong term deployment, Electricity Market Reform budgetary allocations.  RenewableUK would therefore ask for a commitment to a low carbon innovation post 2015 to allow for innovative ideas and solutions to reach a stage where they are able to contribute to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he cost reduction agenda in the case of offshore wind, and the commercialisation of wave and tidal renewables. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Regulatory certainty in the near-term future </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will provide confidence in the contribution renewables are set to make to the UK’s energy mix, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with this will come industry confidence to make the necessary commitments to innovation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  In order to encourage this, innovation for low carbon </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">technologies could be tied to the support mechanisms for renewables in the Contracts for Difference and Renewabl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es Obligation Certificates. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Specific targeting of funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through areas identified as part of the TINA process should guide DECC in launching projects promote innovation across the relevant tiers of the supply chain to advance developments in the low car</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bon technologies, whether this is in for example the construction, installation, operations and maintenance or indeed, the decommissioning phase of projects with goal to reducing the cost of energy.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> A balance between smaller and larger projects needs to be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> struck, with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">identification of funding schemes and their targeting. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Improving coordination across the LCICG members</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and recognising the needs of industry in the various technology focus areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, in theory, should aid DECC </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the allocation of funding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for projects with scopes targeted at technology areas that will bring value to the supply chain and the wider renewables industry. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DECC is actively steering the input of industry into the EU level Industrial Initiatives and Strategi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c Energy Technology (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SET) plan feeding in to the Technology Platforms for wind renewables (TPWind). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  The identification of wind energy as a strategic energy technology by The European Commission, demonstrates wind is set to play </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> role in energy security in the coming years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Initiatives such as the Wind European Industrial Initiative (WIind EII), currently has a UK Stakeholder group, where industry is able to communicate needs and wants in order to steer the input of those representing the UK at WindEII meetings.  Further </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work of this nature where Government engages with industry in order to represent interests at European level is welcomed.  As well providing strong UK representation, the Energy Industrial Initiatives also allow for areas of common interest to be identifie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d between member states, therefore opening up the potential for collaboration in specific innovation areas.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The intr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oduction of Horizon2020 funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, running from 2014 to 2020, will provide a funding route for some companies to access in light of the curre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt uncertainty around low carbon innovation post 2015.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11.5pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.thecrownestate.co.uk/media/305094/offshore-wind-cost-reduction-pathways-study.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.thecrownestate.co.uk/media/305094/offshore-wind-cost-reduction-pathways-study.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-s